### Milestone 12 — Offset-based tier encoding for quantized and adaptive

M11 added signed-offset encoding to the **adaptive** stream at fixed 30-bit precision.
This milestone extends the same idea to two remaining gaps:

**12a — Quantized stream offset tiers (new quantized version)**
The quantized stream still uses absolute unsigned index for all payloads.
With offset encoding and data-driven tier routing the tier depends on the actual
deviation of each ratio from identity, not on the configured `PrecisionBits`.

  Background — why offset changes the tier distribution:
    At 16-bit precision (4–5 sig figs), a NearConstant ±0.01% step:
      absolute index → ~32,769          (just over u8 boundary → u16, 2 bytes)
      signed offset  →      ~1          (well within int8 → u8, 1 byte)
    NeuralWeight's 13% u24 pocket (from TestU24Savings) exists because those
    absolute indices cluster in the low 24-bit range of a 30-bit grid. With offset
    encoding the same ratios may scatter; a dedicated u24 tier (3 bytes) captures
    the savings wherever the offset magnitude falls in (32767, 8388607].

  New stream: versionQuantized = 4 (or next available byte).
  Routing: |off| ≤ 127 → u8 (1B) | ≤ 32767 → u16 (2B) | ≤ 8388607 → u24 (3B) | else u32 (4B).
  Requires new rANS symbols: ClassNormal8 and ClassNormal24.
  No tolerance gate (quantized is always lossy to configured precision).

